    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-05-09T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-05-09T16:00:00-05:00" n="1019"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1019">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">851.4061 Motion Pictures/63: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in France</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Armour</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-05-09T17:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 9, 1929—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>145. Reports in the press have it that French Government is considering solution
                    of film controversy whereby a relatively high tax would be laid on all foreign
                    films entering France and the proceeds thereof would be given to French film
                    industry. Under section 303 of the Tariff Act of 1922,<note n="31"
                        xml:id="d1019fn31">42 Stat. 858, 935.</note> it is apparently mandatory on
                    the Secretary of the Treasury to impose countervailing duties in case of
                    exportation to the United States of any article enjoying directly or indirectly
                    benefit of a bounty or grant upon production in the country of origin.</p>
                <p>In view of Commercial Attaché’s participation in the hearings before the French
                    authorities, the Embassy should guard against possible imputation of
                    responsibility in the event that France, without full knowledge of the possible
                    consequences, should adopt any measure which might require imposition of
                    additional American duties on French films exported to this country.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
